  <p class="blog-title">How To Get The Freelance Life You Want</p>
  <p class="post-body">This is my new office chair and it's changing my life.</p>
  <p class="post-body">It all started after a long work trip to Mexico City where everything was wonderful, inspiring and colourful.</p>
  <p class="post-body">I came home to winter in Toronto and a cold apartment. There was no art on the walls, dirt had piled up in places I hadn't looked at in a long time, and there was an old, wobbly, wooden chair sitting in the middle of my home office.</p>
  <p class="post-body">This chair was slightly depressing and didn't bode well for my work ethic now that I was back home.</p>
  <p class="post-body">So I imagined a new office chair, something that I would be excited to sit in for 8-10 hours a day.</p>
  <p class="post-body">I looked for images online, did some Kijiji searches and quickly gave up because I couldn't afford anything I liked.</p>
  <p class="post-body">Then, BOOM! There it was.</p>
  <p class="blog-strong">It was barely visible at first, sitting off to the side in a warehouse filled with castaway furniture, adorned with a $20 price tag. It was perfect.</p>
  <p class="post-body">I wheeled it up to the cash register with such intensity, the cashiers stopped their conversation and stared at me for a second.</p>
  <p class="post-body">They obviously didn't know I had conjured this chair out of my own imagination.</p>
  <p class="post-body">Don't worry; I'm not about to quote "The Secret."</p>
  <p class="post-body">I know I didn't "manifest" this chair.</p>
  <p class="post-body">I imagined what I wanted, I did some research to see what was out there, and then I purposely went to an old furniture depot to look for it. I drove it home and put it in my apartment myself. It didn't magically appear.</p>
  <p class="post-body">But, now I have something in my home - something I sit on every day - that reminds me I have the ability to imagine things and then make them happen.</p>
  <p class="post-body">That's extremely valuable, because here's the thing:</p>
  <p class="blog-strong">Leaning out to see where you're going helps you get the right stuff done.</p>
  <p class="post-body">It makes sure that all of your hard work is leading you to something that you're actually going to enjoy and be proud of.</span></p>
  <p class="post-body">I don't recommend spending all day daydreaming about what you wish you were doing. There is such a thing as too much thinking, too little doing.</p>
  <p class="post-body">But thinking about the future from time to time helps you focus on the stuff that's really important and say "no" to projects that aren't working out anymore.</p>
  <p class="post-body">And most importantly, future thinking helps you stay the course when things get rough (because things will get rough.)  If you don't know where you're going and why you're going there, you're going to get stressed, burnt out and probably quit.</p>
  <p class="post-body">We don't want to see that happen, so here's how you can get clear on your path:</p>
  <p class="post-body">- Get out a pen and paper.</p>
  <p class="post-body">- Write the date at the top of the page, but make it exactly 5 years in the future. (This act alone can be kind of jarring).</p>
  <p class="post-body">- Write down how old you are, where you're living, who you're with, how much money you're making, how you spend your days, what you're wearing, what you like to eat, your biggest accomplishments, etc.</p>
  <p class="post-body">- Get really clear about what you want and why. Go into as much detail as possible and keep going until you've exhausted your imagination.</p>
  <p class="post-body">- Stash this document somewhere private where you can access it easily, because you're not done.</p>
  <p class="post-body">You'll continue to update and revise this "living" document as you change course, come up with new goals, and knock old ones off your list. Even if you never look at it again, you might be surprised as how accurate it is 5 years from now.<p>
  <p class="post-body italic">This newsletter is a sneak peek at an online course that I'm developing for smart, driven, creative people who want to start freelance journalism careers and get paid.</p>
  <p class="post-body italic">Each week I'll give you a glimpse at the next module, along with special offers that I'll only share with my list, so make sure you sign up!
  <p class="post-body italic">If this article helped you, please share it with your family, friends, colleagues, and classmates. I also post everything on <a href="https://medium.com/@ashleyrenders/i-saved-my-journalism-career-by-making-a-job-for-myself-1ececee060b1#.ksgvz8ezd" class="link-in-body" target="_blank"> Medium,</a> in case you prefer to like and share that way.</p><br><br>
