  <p class="blog-title">How To Get Paid As A Freelancer (Even If You Don't Have Any Clippings)</p>
  <p class="post-body">Before I tell how you to get paid as a freelancer, I want to tell you something important: you're allowed to get paid for your writing.</p>
  <p class="post-body">This might seem obvious, but the first time you have to ask to get paid or defend your fee, you'll probably see a lot (if not all) of your self worth go out the window.</p>
  <p class="post-body">I experienced this first hand last week.</p>
  <p class="post-body">Someone on Facebook criticized me for charging money for my coaching services because it's more honourable to give your advice away for free.</p>
  <p class="blog-strong">This small interaction was my worst nightmare. My hands were sweaty, my chest felt tight, my face turned red. I think my vision might have blurred for a second.</p>
  <p class="post-body">Her message seemed to scream "WHO DO YOU THINK YOU ARE FOR MAKING MONEY?" and for a minute, I was wondering that myself.</p>
  <p class="post-body">I know that I deliver a ton of value to my clients who are wasting time and energy trying to figure out their freelance careers, but this was the first time I had to defend it.</p>
  <p class="post-body">I ended up gaining more clients and followers than any other day, so I guess I did a good job.</p>
  <p class="post-body">But after the dust cleared and I had a glass of wine, I realized this was part of a bigger problem.</p>
  <p class="post-body">When you have the courage to ask for what you're worth, it's always possible that someone might freak out.
  <p class="post-body">Emotions are running high in the journalism industry because scarcity and fear around money is at an all-time high.</p>
  <p class="post-body">Asking for money in that environment is particularly vulnerable and emotionally-loaded. It's a mine field of icky feelings.</p>
  <p class="blog-strong">You might be tempted to work for free - or maybe just watch Netflix and work a day job instead - because it's safer. You can successfully avoid anything that might be even slightly uncomfortable.</p>
  <p class="post-body">Please don't do that.</p>
  <p class="post-body">You are allowed to make money from your gifts, regardless of how much experience you have.</p>
  <p class="post-body">You will be professional and easy to work with. You will put just as much work into creating a flawless piece of writing as any other writer. And you will earn every penny of what you're paid.</p>
  <p class="post-body">Here's how you do that:</p>
  <p class="post-body"><span class="strong">1. Get yourself acquainted with the going rates at various publications.</span></p>
  <p class="post-body">Once you see how many places do pay, you'll realized how ridiculous it is to work for free.</p>
  <p class="post-body"><a href="http://contently.net/rates-database/" class="link-in-body" target="_blank">The Freelancer has a great database of rates.</a> The next time you have a pitch you want to send out, scroll through this list until your story clicks with a publication.</p>
  <p class="post-body"><span class="strong">2. Pitch an amazing story to a smaller publication that pays.</p>
  <p class="post-body">This how you get started as a freelance writer without working for free. You'll slowly build up a portfolio and work up to larger publications over time. Everyone's portfolio starts at zero, so don't let that stop you.</p>
  <p class="post-body">Smaller publications often get overlooked for great stories, so they appreciate a good pitch. And niche publications often pay higher rates than larger companies.</p>
  <p class="post-body"><span class="strong">3. Ask about money right away.</p>
  <p class="post-body">When an editor accepts your story, reply with a friendly email asking about their rates. This is the time to discuss money - not after your story has been published, not when you deliver the final draft.</p>
  <p class="post-body"><span class="strong">4. In fact, don't work on a story until you've negotiated payment.</p>
  <p class="post-body">You will have to do some amount of work to write the pitch, but decide how much time you're willing to put into the pitch and then leave it alone until you get that sweet green money light from an editor.</p>
  <p class="post-body"><span class="strong">5. Get comfortable with talking about money in your regular life.</p>
  <p class="post-body">If you can't talk about money with your friends and family, you're going to have a really hard time getting paid as a freelancer.</p>
  <p class="post-body">This is a big one. If you need help, <a href="http://beingboss.club/podcast/podcast-episode-11-get-paid-like-a-boss" class="link-in-body" target="_blank">check out this amazing episode of Being Boss called "Get Paid Like A Boss."</a> As they say, "money is only as weird as you make it."</p>
  <p class="post-body"><span class="strong">6. Watch this Rihanna performance over and over until you feel better.</p><br>
